Java Streams — Everything You Need for Interviews

What is a Stream?
Think of a Stream as a pipeline through which your data flows and gets processed. It is not a data structure — it does not store data. It takes data from a source (like a List or array), passes it through a series of operations, and produces a result.
The mental model is a factory assembly line: raw materials come in one end, go through multiple processing stations, and a finished product comes out the other end.
javaList<String> names = List.of("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie", "Anna");

List<String> result = names.stream()          // source: creates the pipeline
    .filter(n -> n.startsWith("A"))           // station 1: filter
    .map(String::toUpperCase)                 // station 2: transform
    .collect(Collectors.toList());            // end: collect the result

// result: ["ALICE", "ANNA"]
Three important properties to always remember: streams are not reusable (once consumed, done), they are lazy (nothing runs until a terminal operation is called), and they do not modify the source (the original list is untouched).

Ways to Create a Stream
java// 1. From a Collection — most common
List<String> list = List.of("a", "b", "c");
Stream<String> s1 = list.stream();
Stream<String> s2 = list.parallelStream(); // parallel version

// 2. From individual values — Stream.of()
Stream<String> s3 = Stream.of("x", "y", "z");

// 3. From an array
String[] arr = {"a", "b", "c"};
Stream<String> s4 = Arrays.stream(arr);

// 4. Infinite streams — generate() and iterate()
Stream<Double> randoms = Stream.generate(Math::random);  // infinite: keep producing
Stream<Integer> numbers = Stream.iterate(0, n -> n + 2); // infinite: 0, 2, 4, 6...
// Always use limit() with infinite streams or you'll loop forever
Stream<Integer> first10Even = Stream.iterate(0, n -> n + 2).limit(10);

// 5. Primitive streams — avoids boxing overhead
IntStream range = IntStream.range(1, 6);       // 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 (excludes 6)
IntStream rangeClosed = IntStream.rangeClosed(1, 5); // 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 (includes 5)

Intermediate vs Terminal Operations — The Core Concept
This is the most important conceptual distinction in Streams. Every operation is either one or the other.
Intermediate operations are lazy — they just describe what should happen but don't actually run anything. They return another Stream, which is why you can chain them. filter(), map(), sorted(), distinct(), limit(), skip(), flatMap(), peek() — all intermediate.
Terminal operations are what actually trigger the pipeline to run. Once called, the stream is consumed and cannot be used again. collect(), forEach(), reduce(), count(), findFirst(), findAny(), anyMatch(), allMatch(), noneMatch(), min(), max(), toArray() — all terminal.
A stream with only intermediate operations and no terminal operation does absolutely nothing. This catches people off guard.
java// This does NOTHING — no terminal operation
names.stream().filter(n -> n.startsWith("A")).map(String::toUpperCase);

// This runs — collect() is the terminal operation that triggers everything
List<String> result = names.stream()
    .filter(n -> n.startsWith("A"))
    .map(String::toUpperCase)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

The Important Intermediate Operations
filter(Predicate) — keeps elements that satisfy a condition.
javaList<Integer> evens = List.of(1,2,3,4,5).stream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
    .collect(Collectors.toList()); // [2, 4]
map(Function) — transforms each element into something else. The stream type can change.
javaList<Integer> lengths = List.of("Alice", "Bob").stream()
    .map(String::length)           // Stream<String> → Stream<Integer>
    .collect(Collectors.toList()); // [5, 3]
flatMap(Function) — this one trips people up. Use it when each element maps to a collection, and you want to flatten all those collections into one single stream. Think of it as map + flatten.
javaList<List<Integer>> nested = List.of(List.of(1,2), List.of(3,4), List.of(5));

List<Integer> flat = nested.stream()
    .flatMap(Collection::stream)   // each inner List becomes a Stream, then all merged
    .collect(Collectors.toList()); // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
sorted() — natural order. sorted(Comparator) — custom order.
javaList<String> sorted = List.of("Banana", "Apple", "Cherry").stream()
    .sorted()                              // alphabetical
    .collect(Collectors.toList());         // [Apple, Banana, Cherry]

// Custom sort by length
List<String> byLength = List.of("Banana", "Kiwi", "Apple").stream()
    .sorted(Comparator.comparingInt(String::length))
    .collect(Collectors.toList());         // [Kiwi, Apple, Banana]
distinct() removes duplicates using equals(). limit(n) takes only the first n elements. skip(n) skips the first n elements. These are straightforward.
peek(Consumer) — used for debugging. It lets you look at elements as they flow through the pipeline without changing them. Never use it for real logic — it's purely for inspecting intermediate state during development.
javaList.of(1,2,3,4).stream()
    .filter(n -> n > 2)
    .peek(n -> System.out.println("After filter: " + n)) // debugging
    .map(n -> n * 10)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

The Important Terminal Operations
collect(Collector) — the most versatile terminal operation. Accumulates elements into a container. Almost always used with Collectors utility class.
java// toList, toSet, toMap
List<String> list = stream.collect(Collectors.toList());
Set<String> set   = stream.collect(Collectors.toSet());

// joining — for Strings
String joined = Stream.of("a","b","c").collect(Collectors.joining(", ", "[", "]")); // [a, b, c]

// groupingBy — interview favourite
Map<Integer, List<String>> byLength = Stream.of("Hi","Hello","Hey","Bye")
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(String::length));
// {2: ["Hi"], 5: ["Hello"], 3: ["Hey", "Bye"]}

// counting downstream
Map<Integer, Long> countByLength = Stream.of("Hi","Hello","Hey","Bye")
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(String::length, Collectors.counting()));
// {2: 1, 5: 1, 3: 2}

// partitioningBy — splits into true/false groups
Map<Boolean, List<Integer>> parts = Stream.of(1,2,3,4,5)
    .collect(Collectors.partitioningBy(n -> n % 2 == 0));
// {true: [2,4], false: [1,3,5]}
reduce(identity, BinaryOperator) — collapses all elements into a single value by repeatedly applying a function.
javaint sum = Stream.of(1,2,3,4,5).reduce(0, Integer::sum); // 0+1+2+3+4+5 = 15

// Without identity — returns Optional because stream could be empty
Optional<Integer> max = Stream.of(3,1,4,1,5).reduce((a, b) -> a > b ? a : b);
forEach(Consumer) — iterates and does something; returns void, can't chain after it.
count() — returns long count of elements.
findFirst() and findAny() — both return Optional<T>. findFirst() always returns the first element (deterministic). findAny() returns any element, and is faster in parallel streams because it doesn't enforce ordering.
anyMatch(), allMatch(), noneMatch() — all take a Predicate, all return boolean, all short-circuit (stop processing as soon as the result is known).
javaList<Integer> nums = List.of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
nums.stream().anyMatch(n -> n > 4);  // true  — stops at 5
nums.stream().allMatch(n -> n > 0);  // true  — checks all
nums.stream().noneMatch(n -> n > 10); // true — stops early if any match found
min() and max() — take a Comparator, return Optional<T>.
javaOptional<String> shortest = Stream.of("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie")
    .min(Comparator.comparingInt(String::length)); // Optional["Bob"]

Parallel Streams — Know the Trade-offs
parallelStream() or .parallel() splits the data across multiple CPU cores using the ForkJoin pool. It sounds great but use it carefully.
Use it when: the dataset is large, the operations are CPU-intensive, and there are no shared mutable state or ordering concerns.
Avoid it when: the dataset is small (thread coordination overhead exceeds the gain), operations have side effects, or you need guaranteed encounter order. In most typical business applications, sequential streams are faster.


